tory of Central Europe and analyzes its relation to psychoanalysis, Marxism, musical aesthetics, and the legacy of European modernism.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aFiction. 4aGeneral. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBerman, Russell A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerman, Russell A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aByers, Roger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchnitzler, Arthur, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007774440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091242740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520912427423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520912427/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles